    <h2>we will have small online disscusions about bees</h2>
    <p>this is why we need bees:</p>
    <!-- Add a block quotation -->
    <blockquote>
        We need bees because they are vital pollinators, responsible for the reproduction of about one-third of the
        world's food crops and 75% of flowering plants, ensuring our food supply and a balanced ecosystem. Bees also
        provide high-quality food and products like honey and beeswax, support biodiversity, and indicate the health of
        our natural landscapes. Without bees, many foods would become less available or more expensive, and ecosystems
        would face severe disruption.
        <h2>Pollination and Food Security</h2>
        Crop Reproduction: Bees transfer pollen between flowers, a process essential for plants to produce seeds,
        fruits, and vegetables.
        Global Food Supply: Around 75% of the world's flowering plants rely on pollinators, and a significant portion of
        global food production depends on them, according to the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) of the United
        Nations.
        Increased Yield and Quality: Bees increase both the quantity and quality of many fruits, nuts, and vegetables,
        including apples, berries, melons, and pumpkins.
        Ecological Importance
        Biodiversity: By pollinating wild plants and trees, bees support the habitats and food sources for other
        wildlife, which helps maintain biodiversity.
        Ecosystem Health: Bees play a critical role in maintaining the balance of ecosystems. Their presence indicates
        the health of the local environment and its ability to support varied flora.
        Human and Economic Benefits
        Products: Bees produce valuable products such as honey, royal jelly, pollen, beeswax, and propolis, which have
        medicinal and commercial uses.
        Economic Value: Bees provide billions of dollars' worth of pollination services to agriculture annually,
        supporting farmers and the economy.
        Consequences of Bee Decline
        Food Shortages: A decline in bee populations would lead to food shortages and increased food prices, impacting
        human food security.
        Ecosystem Collapse: The loss of bees would trigger a cascade effect, disrupting food chains and potentially
        leading to the collapse of entire ecosystems.
    </blockquote>

